What is SecurityFilterChain?

SecurityFilterChain is a Spring Security configuration component introduced in Spring Security 5.7+.

It defines how incoming HTTP requests are secured, including:

Authentication
Authorization
Login
Logout
JWT Validation
CSRF
CORS

Before Spring Security 5.7: We used WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter (now deprecated).

Now: We configure security using SecurityFilterChain.

Why Do We Need SecurityFilterChain?

Suppose you have a Banking Application.

You have APIs like:

POST   /login

GET    /accounts

POST   /transfer

GET    /balance

GET    /admin

Requirements:

Everyone can access /login
Only logged-in users can access /accounts
Only ADMIN can access /admin

SecurityFilterChain handles these rules.

Banking Example
@Configuration
@EnableWebSecurity
public class SecurityConfig {

    @Bean
    public SecurityFilterChain securityFilterChain(HttpSecurity http)
            throws Exception {

        http
            .csrf(csrf -> csrf.disable())

            .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth

                .requestMatchers("/login").permitAll()

                .requestMatchers("/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN")

                .requestMatchers("/accounts/**").authenticated()

                .anyRequest().authenticated()
            )

            .formLogin(Customizer.withDefaults());

        return http.build();
    }
}
Explanation
Step 1
http.csrf(csrf -> csrf.disable());

Disables CSRF protection (commonly done for REST APIs using JWT).

Step 2
.authorizeHttpRequests(...)

Defines authorization rules.

Step 3
.requestMatchers("/login").permitAll();

Anyone can access the login API.

Step 4
.requestMatchers("/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN");

Only users with the ADMIN role can access admin endpoints.

Step 5
.requestMatchers("/accounts/**").authenticated();

Users must be logged in.

Step 6
return http.build();

Builds and returns the SecurityFilterChain.

